{"title_page": "Daniel Webster Memorial", "text_new": "{{Infobox nrhp | name =Webster, Daniel, Memorial\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = File:Daniel Webster Memorial - Washington, DC - DSC05553.JPG \n  | caption = \n  | location= [[Washington, D.C.]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|38|54|26|N|77|2|14.2|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Washington, D.C.\n  | built =1900\n| architect= [[Gaetano Trentanove]]\n| architecture= [[Classical Revival]]\n  | added = October 12, 2007\n  | area = less than one acre\n  | governing_body = <!--[[National Park Service]]-->Federal \n  | mpsub = Memorials in Washington, D.C.\n  | refnum = 07001063<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Daniel Webster Memorial''' is a monument in [[Washington, D.C.]] honoring U.S. statesman [[Daniel Webster]]. It is located near Webster's former home at 1603 [[Massachusetts Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue]] [[Northwest, Washington, D.C.|Northwest]], beside [[Scott Circle]] at the intersection of Massachusetts Avenue and [[Rhode Island Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Rhode Island Avenue]]. \n\nThe statue of Webster was given to the [[United States government]] by [[Stilson Hutchins]], founder of the ''[[Washington Post]]'' and a fellow native of New Hampshire.<ref name=\"webster\">{{cite web| last= | first= | title=National Capital Parks | work=| publisher=National Park Service | date= | url=http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/nace/adhia4.htm | accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref> An [[Act of Congress]] on July 1, 1898 authorized its erection on public grounds and appropriated $4,000 for a pedestal. The memorial was dedicated on January 19, 1900.<ref name=\"webster\"/><ref name=daniel>{{Cite book |last=Bednar |first=Michael |year=2006 |title=L'Enfant's Legacy: Public Open Spaces in Washington, D.C. |publisher=JHU Press |pages=163 |isbn=0-8018-8318-0 |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>  On October 12, 2007, the Daniel Webster Memorial was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\"/><ref name=\"daniel\"/>\n\nThe Daniel Webster Memorial consists of a 12-foot (3.7 m) bronze statue of Webster on an 18-foot (5.5 m) granite pedestal in a sober classical style. The statue was sculpted by [[Gaetano Trentanove]].<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite web| title=Daniel Webster, (sculpture)| url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!317634~!0#focus| publisher=Smithsonian Institution Research Information System| date=| accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn the east and west sides of the pedestal are bronze bas-relief panels illustrating events in Webster's life: the [[Webster\u2013Hayne debate]]; the dedication of the [[Bunker Hill Monument]].<ref name=\"panel\">{{cite web| title=Webster, Daniel: Memorial on Scott Circle in Washington, D.C.| publisher=dcmemorials.com | date=24 July 2011 | url=http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0001770.htm | accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>\n\nThe inscription reads:<br>\nG. Trentanove F. Galli Fuseri, Firenze 1898 Italia <br>\n(Front of base:) <br>\nDANIEL WEBSTER<br>\nLIBERTY AND UNION<br>\nNOW AND FOREVER<br>\nONE AND INSEPARABLE <br>\n(Proper left bottom:) <br>\nBORN AT<br>\nSALISBURY, N.H.<br>\nJAN 18, 1782<br>\nDIED AT<br>\nMARSHFIELD MASS<br>\nOCT. 24, 1852 <br>\n(Bottom rear:) <br>\nGIVEN BY STILLSON HUTCHINS<br>\nA NATIVE OF N.H.<br>\nDEDICATED JAN. 18, 1900 <br>\n(Rear top:) <br>\nOUR COUNTRY<br>\nOUR WHOLE COUNTRY<br>\nAND NOTHING BUT<br>\nOUR COUNTRY <br>\n(Proper right, bottom:) <br>\nEXPOUNDER<br>\nAND DEFENDER<br>\nOF THE CONSTITUTION <br>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n* [[List of Registered Historic Places in the District of Columbia]]\n* [[Outdoor sculpture in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons cat|Daniel Webster Memorial}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Washington DC landmarks}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n[[Category:Statues in Washington, D.C.|Webster]]\n[[Category:Embassy Row]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington, D.C.|Webster]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Washington, D.C.|Webster]]\n[[Category:1900 sculptures]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical sculptures]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox nrhp | name =Webster, Daniel, Memorial\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = File:Daniel Webster Memorial - Washington, DC - DSC05553.JPG \n  | caption = \n  | location= [[Washington, D.C.]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|38|54|26|N|77|2|14.2|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = United States Washington, D.C.\n  | built =1900\n| architect= [[Gaetano Trentanove]]\n| architecture= [[Classical Revival]]\n  | added = October 12, 2007\n  | area = less than one acre\n  | governing_body = <!--[[National Park Service]]-->Federal \n  | mpsub = Memorials in Washington, D.C.\n  | refnum = 07001063<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Daniel Webster Memorial''' is a monument in [[Washington, D.C.]] honoring U.S. statesman [[Daniel Webster]]. It is located near Webster's former home at 1603 [[Massachusetts Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Massachusetts Avenue]] [[Northwest, Washington, D.C.|Northwest]], beside [[Scott Circle]] at the intersection of Massachusetts Avenue and [[Rhode Island Avenue (Washington, D.C.)|Rhode Island Avenue]]. \n\nThe statue of Webster was given to the [[United States government]] by [[Stilson Hutchins]], founder of the ''[[Washington Post]]'' and a fellow native of New Hampshire.<ref name=\"webster\">{{cite web| last= | first= | title=National Capital Parks | work=| publisher=National Park Service | date= | url=http://www.nps.gov/history/history/online_books/nace/adhia4.htm | accessdate=2008-06-07}}</ref> An [[Act of Congress]] on July 1, 1898 authorized its erection on public grounds and appropriated $4,000 for a pedestal. The memorial was dedicated on January 19, 1900.<ref name=\"webster\"/><ref name=daniel>{{Cite book |last=Bednar |first=Michael |year=2006 |title=L'Enfant's Legacy: Public Open Spaces in Washington, D.C. |publisher=JHU Press |pages=163 |isbn=0-8018-8318-0 |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>  On October 12, 2007, the Daniel Webster Memorial was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\"/><ref name=\"daniel\"/>\n\nThe Daniel Webster Memorial consists of a 12-foot (3.7 m) bronze statue of Webster on an 18-foot (5.5 m) granite pedestal in a sober classical style. The statue was sculpted by [[Gaetano Trentanove]].<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite web| title=Daniel Webster, (sculpture)| url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!317634~!0#focus| publisher=Smithsonian Institution Research Information System| date=| accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>\n\nOn the east and west sides of the pedestal are bronze bas-relief panels illustrating events in Webster's life: the [[Webster\u2013Hayne debate]]; the dedication of the [[Bunker Hill Monument]].<ref name=\"panel\">{{cite web| title=Webster, Daniel: Memorial on Scott Circle in Washington, D.C.| publisher=dcmemorials.com | date=24 July 2011 | url=http://dcmemorials.com/index_indiv0001770.htm | accessdate=2011-07-26}}</ref>\n\nThe inscription reads:<br>\nG. Trentanove F. Galli Fuseri, Firenze 1898 Italia <br>\n(Front of base:) <br>\nDANIEL WEBSTER<br>\nLIBERTY AND UNION<br>\nNOW AND FOREVER<br>\nONE AND INSEPARABLE <br>\n(Proper left bottom:) <br>\nBORN AT<br>\nSALISBURY, N.H.<br>\nJAN 18, 1782<br>\nDIED AT<br>\nMARSHFIELD MASS<br>\nOCT. 24, 1852 <br>\n(Bottom rear:) <br>\nGIVEN BY STILLSON HUTCHINS<br>\nA NATIVE OF N.H.<br>\nDEDICATED JAN. 18, 1900 <br>\n(Rear top:) <br>\nOUR COUNTRY<br>\nOUR WHOLE COUNTRY<br>\nAND NOTHING BUT<br>\nOUR COUNTRY <br>\n(Proper right, bottom:) <br>\nEXPOUNDER<br>\nAND DEFENDER<br>\nOF THE CONSTITUTION <br>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n* [[List of Registered Historic Places in the District of Columbia]]\n* [[Outdoor sculpture in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons cat|Daniel Webster Memorial}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Washington DC landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Statues in Washington, D.C.|Webster]]\n[[Category:Embassy Row]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington, D.C.|Webster]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of men in Washington, D.C.|Webster]]\n[[Category:1900 sculptures]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical sculptures]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Template:Public art in Washington, D.C.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Webster_Memorial"}
{"title_page": "Eric Bazilian", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Eric Bazilian\n| image            = Ericbazilian.jpg\n| caption          = Eric Bazilian (2008)\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Eric Michael Bazilian\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1953|7|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, United States\n| death_date       = \n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[melodica]], saxophone, [[mandolin]], keyboards, bass, drums\n| genre            = Rock\n| occupation       = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active     = 1978\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[The Hooters]]\n| website          = {{url|ericbazilian.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Eric M. Bazilian''' (born July 21, 1953), is an American singer, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist, arranger and producer, best known for being a founding member of the rock band [[The Hooters]] and for writing \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]],\" made famous by [[Joan Osborne]] in 1995.\n\n==Early life==\nEric Michael Bazilian was born at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] Hospital in [[Philadelphia]] to a father who was a [[psychiatrist]] and a mother who was a concert pianist. He is Jewish.\n\nHe began playing the piano at age five, and his uncle taught him guitar at nine. He never took formal musical lessons. At the age of 10, while watching [[The Beatles]] on [[The Ed Sullivan Show]], Bazilian realized that playing and creating music was what he wished to pursue with his life.\n\nAt 16 years old, while attending [[Germantown Friends School]], Bazilian started writing songs for his first band, Evil Seed. This band played all original music at \"Be-ins\" at Belmont Plateau in [[Fairmount Park]].\n\nBy the mid 1970s, while attending the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he earned a Bachelor of Science degree in [[Physics]], Bazilian met [[Rob Hyman]] and [[Rick Chertoff]], with whom he formed a band called Baby Grand. They would release two albums during their tenure.\n\n==Tenure with The Hooters==\nAfter Baby Grand disbanded, Hyman and Bazilian decided to try something new by combining [[reggae]], [[ska]], and [[rock'n'roll]] to create [[The Hooters]] in 1980.\n\n''[[Nervous Night (album)|Nervous Night]]'', [[The Hooters]]' 1985 debut on [[Columbia Records]], sold more than 2 million copies and included ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' Top 40 hits \"Day By Day\" (#18), \"[[And We Danced (The Hooters song)|And We Danced]]\" (#21) and \"Where Do The Children Go\" (#38).\n\nAfter releasing six albums, [[The Hooters]] obtained a large global following throughout the 1980s and 1990s. As a result, they were asked to open three major musical events of the late 20th century: [[Live Aid]] in [[Philadelphia]] in 1985, [[Amnesty International]] Concert at [[Giants Stadium]] in 1986, and [[Roger Waters]]' [[The Wall Concert in Berlin]] in 1990.  In 1995, The Hooters went on hiatus, although Hyman and Bazilian would continue to collaborate on musical projects for other artists.\n\nBazilian reunited with The Hooters on successful headlining European summer tours in 2003, 2004, and 2005.\n\n2007 saw the release of ''[[Time Stand Still]]'', their first album of new material since 1993.\n\nIn 2009, they released \"[[Both Sides Live]]\", a double CD which featured a concert at Philadelphia's Electric Factory as well as a special acoustic performance recorded at [[Rob Hyman]]'s Elm Street Studios.\n\nIn 2010, to celebrate 30 years as a band, they released a five song EP entitled \"[[Five By Five]]\", produced by [[Nick Jameson]]. The EP featured the only \"official\" studio recordings by the band of Rob Hyman's \"[[Time After Time (Cyndi Lauper song)|Time After Time]]\" and Bazilian's \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]]\".\n\nThe Hooters continue to tour successfully in Germany and Scandinavia and perform special concert events in their native [[Philadelphia]].\n\n==\"One of Us\"==\nBazilian has become recognized internationally for being a songwriter, [[session musician]], arranger, and producer for many artists.\n\nIn 1995, he played all those roles for [[Joan Osborne]]'s major-label debut album ''[[Relish (album)|Relish]],'' which was nominated for six [[Grammy Awards]], including [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] for the No. 4 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' hit \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]],\" which Bazilian wrote.\n\n\"One of Us\" has since been covered by many artists throughout the world, among them being [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Doctor Evil]] in ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'', [[Martyn Joseph]], Scott Bradoka, Sharla Jackson Band, Wildside, Jackie \"O\", [[DJ Irene]], [[Outta Control]], and [[Seal (musician)|Seal]].\n\nIn 2003, \"One of Us\" was used as the [[theme song]] for the [[CBS]] television series ''[[Joan of Arcadia]]''. It has also appeared on the soundtracks of numerous movies, including ''[[Vanilla Sky]]'' (2001), ''[[Bruce Almighty]]'', (2003) and ''[[Diary of a Mad Black Woman (film)|Diary of a Mad Black Woman]]'' (2005).\n\nIn more recent years, [[The Hooters]] have also performed \"One of Us\" in their live shows.\n\n==Recognitions==\nOn November 17, 2000, Bazilian was inducted into the Philadelphia Walk of Fame on the [[Avenue of the Arts, Philadelphia|Avenue of the Arts]].<ref>[http://www.philadelphiamusicalliance.org/walk_names.htm#b] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727173419/http://www.philadelphiamusicalliance.org/walk_names.htm |date=July 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2004, Bazilian won an [[ASCAP]] Film and Television Music Award for \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]]\" as the [[theme song]] for the [[CBS]] television series ''[[Joan of Arcadia]]''.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo career===\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''The Optimist'' (2000)\n| title1          = Driving in England\n| length1         = 4:19\n| title2          = Until You Dare\n| length2         = 4:17\n| title3          = Gemini Yo Yo\n| length3         = 4:32\n| title4          = Bye Bye Baby\n| length4         = 5:24\n| title5          = U.G.L.Y.\n| length5         = 3:45\n| title6          = When I Was the Man\n| length6         = 3:54\n| title7          = Kid from Outer Space\n| length7         = 5:03\n| title8          = By My Woman\n| length8         = 4:46\n| title9          = Fiddlesticks\n| length9         = 4:03\n| title10         = Hopelessly, Relentlessly\n| length10        = 5:11\n| title11         = Mind Going Down\n| length11        = 3:27\n| title12         = The Optimist / One of Us (Demo) [hidden track]\n| length12        = 9:30\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''A Very Dull Boy'' (2002)\n| title1          = A Very Dull Boy\n| length1         = 5:03\n| title2          = Lucky to Be\n| length2         = 2:27\n| title3          = Insomnia\n| length3         = 3:26\n| title4          = Since You Ask\n| length4         = 2:47\n| title5          = Feeling Your Pain\n| length5         = 3:22\n| title6          = A Pocket Full of Nothing\n| length6         = 3:33\n| title7          = Ella Fitzgerald\n| length7         = 3:35\n| title8          = Too Much of My Time\n| length8         = 4:38\n| title9          = Lump of Clay\n| length9         = 3:25\n| title10         = Hallelujah and Amen\n| length10        = 3:24\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''What Shall Become of the Baby?'' (2012) (with [[Mats Wester]], as Bazilian & Wester)\n| title1          = Good Thing\n| length1         = 2:57\n| title2          = Until You Dare\n| length2         = 4:58\n| title3          = These Three Chords\n| length3         = 3:41\n| title4          = Bone\n| length4         = 4:31\n| title5          = Bigger Than the Bossa Nova\n| length5         = 3:36\n| title6          = Somebody Else\n| length6         = 3:42\n| title7          = Over the Hill\n| length7         = 3:26\n| title8          = The Man\n| length8         = 3:32\n| title9          = What People Got to Do\n| length9         = 5:09\n| title10         = Stureplan\n| length10        = 4:20\n| title11         = What Shall Become of the Baby\n| length11        = 4:03\n| title12         = Where Your Angels Are\n| length12        = 4:18\n}}\n\n===Songwriter===\nBazilian has (co-)written songs for numerous artists throughout the world, among them:\n* [[Billie Myers]] \u2013 \"Kiss The Rain\"\n* [[Robbie Williams]] \u2013 \"[[Old Before I Die]]\"\n* [[Joan Osborne]] \u2013 \"Dracula Moon\"; \"Ladder\"; \"Let's Just Get Naked\"; \"Lumina\"; \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]]\"; \"Pensacola\"; \"Right Hand Man\"; \"Saint Teresa\"\n* [[Amanda Marshall]] \u2013 \"Believe in You\"; \"Best of Me\"; \"Give Up Giving In\"; \"If I Didn't Have You\"; \"Love Lift Me\"; \"Never Said Goodbye\"; \"Ride\"; \"Shades of Grey\"; \"Too Little Too Late\"; \"Why Don't You Love Me\"\n* [[Ricky Martin]] \u2013 \"[[Private Emotion]]\"\n* [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]] \u2013 \"Remember the Good Times\"; \"Dreamers\"; \"[[Humanity (Scorpions song)|Humanity]]\"; \"We Were Born To Fly\"; \"The Future Never Dies\"; \"You're Lovin' Me To Death\"; \"Love Will Keep Us Alive\"; \"Your Last Song\"; \"Cold\"; \"She Said\"; \"Slave Me\"; \"No Limit\"; \"Lorelei\"; \"Spirit of Rock\"; \"Let's Rock\"; \"The Best is Yet to Come\"\n* [[Annie Carrier]] \u2013 \"Attitude\"\n* [[Sarah Hudson (singer)|Sarah Hudson]] \u2013 \"Girl on the Verge\"; \"Little\"\n* [[Des'ree]] \u2013 \"God Only Knows\"\n* [[Bijou Phillips]] \u2013 \"Hawaii\"; \"Just Look Around\"\n* [[Patty Smyth]] \u2013 \"Heartache Heard Around the World\"; \"Never Enough\"\n* [[Willie Nile]] - \"God Laughs\"\n* [[Alejandra Guzm\u00e1n]] \u2013 \"Hoy Me Voy A Querer\"\n* [[Bon Jovi]] \u2013 \"I Get a Rush\"; \"One Man Band\"\n* [[Bif Naked]] \u2013 \"I Love Myself Today\"\n* [[The Calling]] \u2013 \"Just That Good\"; \"Stigmatized\"\n* [[Jonatha Brooke]] \u2013 \"Less Than Love is Nothing\"\n* [[Ronnie Spector]] \u2013 \"Never Gonna Be Your Baby\"\n* [[Shannon McNally]] \u2013 \"Now That I Know\"\n* [[Zucchero]] \u2013 \"Pure Love\"\n* [[LeAnn Rimes]] \u2013 \"Safest Place\"\n* [[Cyndi Lauper]] \u2013 \"Someone Like Me\"; \"[[That's What I Think]]\"\n* [[Matt Nathanson]] \u2013 \"Suspended\"\n* [[Alannah Myles]] \u2013 \"Bad 4 You\"\n* [[D-Side]] \u2013 \"My Best Chance\"\n* [[Jon Bon Jovi]] \u2013 \"Sad Song Night\"; \"Ugly\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://online.gema.de/werke/search.faces|title=GEMA - Members - Online Database - Musical Works|website=online.gema.de}}</ref>\n* [[Journey (band)|Journey]] \u2013 \"To Be Alive Again\"\n* [[Leah Andreone]] \u2013 \"Inconceivable\"\n* [[Lucia Cifarelli]] \u2013 \"We Are Angels\"\n* [[Midge Ure]] \u2013 \"Fallen Angel\"\n* [[Nordman]] \u2013 \"Hj\u00e4lp Mig Att Leva\"; \" Sorg Min \u00c4lskarinna\"\n* [[Tommy Conwell and the Young Rumblers]] \u2013 \"Half A Heart\"\n* Theme to the TV series [[Dollhouse (TV series)|\"Dollhouse]]\" \u2013 (Co-writer with Jonatha Brooke)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbazilian.com/ Eric Bazilian] official website\n*[https://www.myspace.com/ericbazilian Eric Bazilian] official MySpace page\n*{{IMDb name|id=1709552|name=Eric Bazilian}}\n\n{{The Hooters}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bazilian, Eric}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:The Hooters members]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Germantown Friends School alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Eric Bazilian\n| image = Ericbazilian.jpg\n| caption = Eric Bazilian (2008)\n| image_size =\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Eric Michael Bazilian\n| alias =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|7|21}} \n|birth_place =[[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, US\n| death_date =\n| instrument = Vocals, guitar, [[melodica]], saxophone, [[mandolin]], keyboards, bass, drums\n| genre = Rock\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| label =\n| associated_acts = [[The Hooters]]\n| website ={{url|ericbazilian.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Eric M. Bazilian''' (born July 21, 1953), is an American singer, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist, arranger and producer, best known for being a founding member of the rock band [[The Hooters]] and for writing \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]],\" made famous by [[Joan Osborne]] in 1995.\n\n==Early life==\nEric Michael Bazilian was born at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] Hospital in [[Philadelphia]] to a father who was a [[psychiatrist]] and a mother who was a concert pianist. He is Jewish.\n\nHe began playing the piano at age five, and his uncle taught him guitar at nine. He never took formal musical lessons. At the age of 10, while watching [[The Beatles]] on [[The Ed Sullivan Show]], Bazilian realized that playing and creating music was what he wished to pursue with his life.\n\nAt 16 years old, while attending [[Germantown Friends School]], Bazilian started writing songs for his first band, Evil Seed. This band played all original music at \"Be-ins\" at Belmont Plateau in [[Fairmount Park]].\n\nBy the mid 1970s, while attending the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he earned a Bachelor of Science degree in [[Physics]], Bazilian met [[Rob Hyman]] and [[Rick Chertoff]], with whom he formed a band called Baby Grand. They would release two albums during their tenure.\n\n==Tenure with The Hooters==\nAfter Baby Grand disbanded, Hyman and Bazilian decided to try something new by combining [[reggae]], [[ska]], and [[rock'n'roll]] to create [[The Hooters]] in 1980.\n\n''[[Nervous Night (album)|Nervous Night]]'', [[The Hooters]]' 1985 debut on [[Columbia Records]], sold more than 2 million copies and included ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' Top 40 hits \"Day By Day\" (#18), \"[[And We Danced (The Hooters song)|And We Danced]]\" (#21) and \"Where Do The Children Go\" (#38).\n\nAfter releasing six albums, [[The Hooters]] obtained a large global following throughout the 1980s and 1990s. As a result, they were asked to open three major musical events of the late 20th century: [[Live Aid]] in [[Philadelphia]] in 1985, [[Amnesty International]] Concert at [[Giants Stadium]] in 1986, and [[Roger Waters]]' [[The Wall Concert in Berlin]] in 1990.  In 1995, The Hooters went on hiatus, although Hyman and Bazilian would continue to collaborate on musical projects for other artists.\n\nBazilian reunited with The Hooters on successful headlining European summer tours in 2003, 2004, and 2005.\n\n2007 saw the release of ''[[Time Stand Still]]'', their first album of new material since 1993.\n\nIn 2009, they released \"[[Both Sides Live]]\", a double CD which featured a concert at Philadelphia's Electric Factory as well as a special acoustic performance recorded at [[Rob Hyman]]'s Elm Street Studios.\n\nIn 2010, to celebrate 30 years as a band, they released a five song EP entitled \"[[Five By Five]]\", produced by [[Nick Jameson]]. The EP featured the only \"official\" studio recordings by the band of Rob Hyman's \"[[Time After Time (Cyndi Lauper song)|Time After Time]]\" and Bazilian's \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]]\".\n\nThe Hooters continue to tour successfully in Germany and Scandinavia and perform special concert events in their native [[Philadelphia]].\n\n==\"One of Us\"==\nBazilian has become recognized internationally for being a songwriter, [[session musician]], arranger, and producer for many artists.\n\nIn 1995, he played all those roles for [[Joan Osborne]]'s major-label debut album ''[[Relish (album)|Relish]],'' which was nominated for six [[Grammy Awards]], including [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] for the No. 4 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' hit \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]],\" which Bazilian wrote.\n\n\"One of Us\" has since been covered by many artists throughout the world, among them being [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Doctor Evil]] in ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'', [[Martyn Joseph]], Scott Bradoka, Sharla Jackson Band, Wildside, Jackie \"O\", [[DJ Irene]], [[Outta Control]], and [[Seal (musician)|Seal]].\n\nIn 2003, \"One of Us\" was used as the [[theme song]] for the [[CBS]] television series ''[[Joan of Arcadia]]''. It has also appeared on the soundtracks of numerous movies, including ''[[Vanilla Sky]]'' (2001), ''[[Bruce Almighty]]'', (2003) and ''[[Diary of a Mad Black Woman (film)|Diary of a Mad Black Woman]]'' (2005).\n\nIn more recent years, [[The Hooters]] have also performed \"One of Us\" in their live shows.\n\n==Recognitions==\nOn November 17, 2000, Bazilian was inducted into the Philadelphia Walk of Fame on the [[Avenue of the Arts, Philadelphia|Avenue of the Arts]].<ref>[http://www.philadelphiamusicalliance.org/walk_names.htm#b] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727173419/http://www.philadelphiamusicalliance.org/walk_names.htm |date=July 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 21, 2004, Bazilian won an [[ASCAP]] Film and Television Music Award for \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]]\" as the [[theme song]] for the [[CBS]] television series ''[[Joan of Arcadia]]''.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo career===\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''The Optimist'' (2000)\n| title1          = Driving in England\n| length1         = 4:19\n| title2          = Until You Dare\n| length2         = 4:17\n| title3          = Gemini Yo Yo\n| length3         = 4:32\n| title4          = Bye Bye Baby\n| length4         = 5:24\n| title5          = U.G.L.Y.\n| length5         = 3:45\n| title6          = When I Was the Man\n| length6         = 3:54\n| title7          = Kid from Outer Space\n| length7         = 5:03\n| title8          = By My Woman\n| length8         = 4:46\n| title9          = Fiddlesticks\n| length9         = 4:03\n| title10         = Hopelessly, Relentlessly\n| length10        = 5:11\n| title11         = Mind Going Down\n| length11        = 3:27\n| title12         = The Optimist / One of Us (Demo) [hidden track]\n| length12        = 9:30\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''A Very Dull Boy'' (2002)\n| title1          = A Very Dull Boy\n| length1         = 5:03\n| title2          = Lucky to Be\n| length2         = 2:27\n| title3          = Insomnia\n| length3         = 3:26\n| title4          = Since You Ask\n| length4         = 2:47\n| title5          = Feeling Your Pain\n| length5         = 3:22\n| title6          = A Pocket Full of Nothing\n| length6         = 3:33\n| title7          = Ella Fitzgerald\n| length7         = 3:35\n| title8          = Too Much of My Time\n| length8         = 4:38\n| title9          = Lump of Clay\n| length9         = 3:25\n| title10         = Hallelujah and Amen\n| length10        = 3:24\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline        = ''What Shall Become of the Baby?'' (2012) (with [[Mats Wester]], as Bazilian & Wester)\n| title1          = Good Thing\n| length1         = 2:57\n| title2          = Until You Dare\n| length2         = 4:58\n| title3          = These Three Chords\n| length3         = 3:41\n| title4          = Bone\n| length4         = 4:31\n| title5          = Bigger Than the Bossa Nova\n| length5         = 3:36\n| title6          = Somebody Else\n| length6         = 3:42\n| title7          = Over the Hill\n| length7         = 3:26\n| title8          = The Man\n| length8         = 3:32\n| title9          = What People Got to Do\n| length9         = 5:09\n| title10         = Stureplan\n| length10        = 4:20\n| title11         = What Shall Become of the Baby\n| length11        = 4:03\n| title12         = Where Your Angels Are\n| length12        = 4:18\n}}\n\n===Songwriter===\nBazilian has (co-)written songs for numerous artists throughout the world, among them:\n* [[Billie Myers]] \u2013 \"Kiss The Rain\"\n* [[Robbie Williams]] \u2013 \"[[Old Before I Die]]\"\n* [[Joan Osborne]] \u2013 \"Dracula Moon\"; \"Ladder\"; \"Let's Just Get Naked\"; \"Lumina\"; \"[[One of Us (Joan Osborne song)|One of Us]]\"; \"Pensacola\"; \"Right Hand Man\"; \"Saint Teresa\"\n* [[Amanda Marshall]] \u2013 \"Believe in You\"; \"Best of Me\"; \"Give Up Giving In\"; \"If I Didn't Have You\"; \"Love Lift Me\"; \"Never Said Goodbye\"; \"Ride\"; \"Shades of Grey\"; \"Too Little Too Late\"; \"Why Don't You Love Me\"\n* [[Ricky Martin]] \u2013 \"[[Private Emotion]]\"\n* [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]] \u2013 \"Remember the Good Times\"; \"Dreamers\"; \"[[Humanity (Scorpions song)|Humanity]]\"; \"We Were Born To Fly\"; \"The Future Never Dies\"; \"You're Lovin' Me To Death\"; \"Love Will Keep Us Alive\"; \"Your Last Song\"; \"Cold\"; \"She Said\"; \"Slave Me\"; \"No Limit\"; \"Lorelei\"; \"Spirit of Rock\"; \"Let's Rock\"; \"The Best is Yet to Come\"\n* [[Annie Carrier]] \u2013 \"Attitude\"\n* [[Sarah Hudson (singer)|Sarah Hudson]] \u2013 \"Girl on the Verge\"; \"Little\"\n* [[Des'ree]] \u2013 \"God Only Knows\"\n* [[Bijou Phillips]] \u2013 \"Hawaii\"; \"Just Look 